			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ever since I started reading the forums, I've noticed the term "bazaar mage" sprinkled here and there. Generally, this term has meant little to me. I, for one, see a mage as a mage as a mage as a...you get the picture. It doesn't matter to me if you are lvl 15, still in your newbie gear, and don't even know you have already earned several new sets of spells by that point. Nor does it matter if you are in Time, with the strongest guild on any server, have 4 bajillion hp and even more mp, raid hardcore eight days a week, thirty-six hours a day. You are the SAME class, as far as I am concerned.
<br />

<br />
But something has irked me a little as of late about this term, especially as far as the GoD spell debacle has been concerned. Now...<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="font-style: italic"><span style="text-decoration: underline">I MAY BE WRONG</span></span></span> (so if I am, don't bite my head off),  but it seems to me a lot of you are in favor of removing the nodrop tag from the spells and/or increasing the drop rate. However--and I cannot remember the post(s) where this was said--very few supported the idea of putting the spells on a vendor. I *do* remember fondly a line someone griped about someone working their butts off for a spell then having a bazaar mage come in and buy the same exact spell with little effort and a lot of platinum, and how unfair that is.
<br />

<br />
While there should be rewards and perks for being more "assertive" in your gameplay (IE the Ancient line of spells), I can't think of any justifiable reason why NOT to put spells on a vendor. Spells are the most basic trait we all share among us all. By instituting the idea that "Well, only those that raid hardcore can even have a shot at these spells" you are creating a situation where members of the same class cannot gain access to that which they have the RIGHT to access, as defined by their class. How can a person who does not have access to the very foundation of their abilities be able to contribute? Image if CH was only obtainable by a raiding cleric, or if slow spells were obtainable by raiding chanters/bsts/shms? I know that would probably make you raiding mages grin with delight, but imagine what would happen to the other 9/10ths of the game.
<br />

<br />
Put all the spells except Ancients on vendors. Make them reasonably priced. If the developers are bent on making spells that can only be gained by raids and/or great effort, design them to provide great utility or some kind hyper-powered nuke that is a world away from anything in a current player's arsenal. This is to entice people into waiting to get them, to get them to unite. A piddily extra...what? 200? 300? 400 extra points (I'm not adding criticals because, to me, they cannot be relied upon with great certainty) and a new resist base doesn't count on this. Just because a certain pet is designed to help in a certain kind of encounter (IE raids and the MS4 pet) doesn't mean that your common mages shouldn't be allowed access to it. You may argue "well, they have the PoP pets, that's good enough for them!" it doesn't excuse the fact that you are taking away something which is rightfully theirs by basis of what their class is (Mage class? Don't we use that funny little guy with the whacky dance moves to kill icky things?).
<br />

<br />
Gear, on the other hand, is a different story. A raiding mage and a bazaar mage SHOULD be drastically different in gear. It is, after all, equipment we find and quest and work for. In fact, I think raiding gear should shift its focus away from obscene stats to providing some utility in a raiding situation. Clicky effects can only help to increase one's role in a raid, but, then again, it would also help one to solo, and this, by virtue of the Dev Gods, <span style="font-weight: bold">IS TEH DEBIL</span>. But that's another story.
<br />

<br />
I realize I could write a fifteen-page post on this subject, and, if I added the whole PoP spell system, I could go into the triple digits, but I think I will cease here. If this is in the wrong forum, or if I paraphrased or took anything the wrong way, I apologize. But it seems to me that someone, somewhere, has to start standing up for the "Bazaar Mage" in at least one area we have in common. Maybe someone has? /shrug
<br />

<br />
Least it was good therapy.<br />_________________<br />"Roads? Where we're going, we don't need roads," --Your friendly neighborhood bus driver</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
